What I tell my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I travel often abroad and my foreign friends always ask me, with varying degrees of bewilderment: what is going on in your country, anyway?
This is what I tell them.
First, do not misconstrue the 2016 elections.
Contrary to some comments, the American political system has not been swept up in a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against elites.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet, Trump lost the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the election by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand more votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
Nevertheless, Trump's victory raises the real issue of the rise of social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the huge difference between California and Appalachia.
Research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income whites without college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically occupied the bottom rung of inequalities.
In 1999, mortality rates among whites without college education were around 30% below those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30% higher.
Moreover, employment in manufacturing, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for working-class whites, has sharply declined over the last generation, making up only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were swayed by Trump's promises to shake things up and bring back industrial jobs.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may well make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that you should not underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and his scandalous disregard for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is monopolizing viewers' attention, and the best way to do that is to make extreme statements, regardless of the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What irritates commentators in the media and academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he shifts from his constant campaign centered on himself to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who loses the popular vote moves towards the political center to attract more support.
This is what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
On the other hand, Trump proclaims that he won the popular vote and, by acting as if this were really the case, pleases his base voters.
While Trump made solid centrist appointments to the Department of Defense, State, and National Security, his picks for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services position him at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists – and he intends to satisfy both camps.
Fourthly, we must not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
Despite their many problems, the United States is not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as divided.
In the design of the US Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure a harmonious government, but to limit political power through a system of checks and balances that makes it difficult to exercise that power.
A joke goes that the founders created a political system such that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us – impossible for him or anyone else.
Ineffectiveness has been put to the service of freedom.
Trump's presidency is still in its early days, and we cannot be certain what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
However, so far, the courts, Congress, and the states have watched over this balance of powers within the administration, according to Madison's wishes.
And permanent executive branch officials still carry weight.
Finally, my friends wonder what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Honestly, I don't know, but I worry less about China's rise than about Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead by providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite problems with the international order under US leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can assert with certainty that it will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational problems.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's statements and those of his administration suggest that he may persist.
After all, the power to constrain and the power to convince the United States come largely from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's commons, is more uncertain.
The Trump Budget Director talks about a power-constraining budget, with cuts made to the State Department and the UN system.
Other government members advocate for replacing multilateral trade agreements with "fair and balanced" bilateral arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to reassure them about these issues.
But I cannot.
